('HR/People', 'mid', 'The Policy Exception', 'A high performer asks for an exception to the remote work policy that others do not get. Granting it could cause resentment. What do you do?', '[{"id":"A","label":"Deny it—policy applies to everyone equally","why_it_matters":"Shows fairness commitment","signals":["equity focus","policy adherence"]},{"id":"B","label":"Grant it quietly, document the business case for exceptions","why_it_matters":"Shows flexibility for retention","signals":["pragmatic retention","exception management"]},{"id":"C","label":"Use this as input to revisit the policy for everyone","why_it_matters":"Shows systems thinking","signals":["policy improvement","systemic fairness"]}]', '["culture_alignment", "problem_solving_vectors"]', 'Each choice reflects valid HR philosophy.'),
('HR/People', 'senior', 'The Toxic Star', 'A top performer is causing team dysfunction. They deliver results but others complain about their behavior. What do you do?', '[{"id":"A","label":"Address the behavior directly—results do not excuse toxicity","why_it_matters":"Shows values enforcement","signals":["culture protection","behavioral accountability"]},{"id":"B","label":"Coach them on impact—sometimes top performers are unaware","why_it_matters":"Shows developmental approach","signals":["coaching mindset","benefit of the doubt"]},{"id":"C","label":"Start documentation for potential exit while coaching","why_it_matters":"Shows prepared pragmatism","signals":["risk management","parallel paths"]}]', '["communication_style", "culture_alignment"]', 'All approaches prioritize team health.'),
